/** 
\page productspage Meteorological products


\tableofcontents

\section products Product generation

Primarily, \b Rack computes meteorological products in polar
coordinate system.  The resulting product is also in polar
coordinates, hence called a \b polar \b product.  It can be also
called as an intermediate product because such a product is often processed
further on, for example added to a composite or transformed to a
Cartesian single-radar image.  This design feature adds speed to
production since many final products can be computed from the same
polar product.  This also facilitates developing the software, as a
new meteorological algorithm needs to be programmed in a single
module only.

By default, generation of a product removes the previous product from memory. Alternatively, several products can be written in the same output structure
by issuing \c --append \c dataset or \c --append \c data (with optional index) before the product commands.. 


The rest of this section handles computation of \em polar \em products. Since end products are most often 
viewed in Cartesian coordinates and coloured, the examples include the Cartesian conversion (\c -c) and palette operation (\c --palette ). 
A quality field, when provided by the product operator, is attached right of the actual product image. 

As processing and using Doppler data involves special aspects, it is handled in it own section, \ref doppler.

\subsection cappi  PseudoCAPPI

Constant-altitude position indicator (CAPPI) is obtained with \c --pCappi command. It takes
altitude as its first argument. 

\~exec
SELECT=dataset1:3 NICK=DEFAULT     PROD=pCappi,1000,weightMin=0,beamWidth=0.5    ./make-image-product.sh #exec
SELECT=dataset1:3 NICK=PSEUDOCAPPI PROD=pCappi,1000,weightMin=-0.1,beamWidth=0.5 ./make-image-product.sh #exec
SELECT=dataset1:3 NICK=CAPPI       PROD=pCappi,1000,weightMin=+0.1,beamWidth=0.5 ./make-image-product.sh #exec
\~
\include pCappi.exm

The Pseudo CAPPI product is computed by traversing \em all the bins of the volume data. The bins are
weighted using an exponential function of the distance from reference altitude. 
This method allows using measurement data from upper and lower beams, when data has low quality or data is missing 
in the closest bins.  

\b Rack supports computing three variations of CAPPI. They differ in ways <i> vertically distant data</i> – bins far below and above the 
requested altitude – near and far from the radar hence are handled.

- CAPPI: \c weightMin > 0, dropping low-quality areas ie. marking them with \c nodata , resulting in an annular shaped image  
- Pseudo CAPPI: \c weightMin < 0, including data far off the nominal altitude
- Default CAPPI: \c weightMin = 0, dropping low-quality areas ie. marking them with \c undetect , resulting in an annular shaped image  

\~remark
The strict, annular CAPPI: vertically distant measurements are marked with \c nodata (obtained with weightMin > 0)
The pseudo CAPPI: also vertically distant measurements are included; obtained by setting a negative value (eg. weightMin=-0.1)
The compromized CAPPI which replaces distant data with \c undetect . (obtained with weightMin=0)
\~

The images below illustrate these variations. Virtual beam width has been set smaller (0.5) to visualize the differences and the quality field. 

\image html  CAPPI-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The CAPPI product and its quality field." 
\image latex CAPPI-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The CAPPI product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth

\image html  PSEUDOCAPPI-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The Pseudo CAPPI product and its quality field." 
\image latex PSEUDOCAPPI-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The Pseudo CAPPI product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth

\image html  DEFAULT-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The 'compromized' CAPPI product and its quality field." 
\image latex DEFAULT-pCappi-DBZH-panel.png "The 'compromized' CAPPI product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth




As a default setting, the relative quality of \c undetect bins is lower than that of detected signals;
this affects e.g. creation of radar image composites. 
The relative quality can be changed with \c --undetectWeight command. 




\subsection maxEcho  Maximum echo

Maximum reflectivity in vertical direction is obtained \c --maxEcho command. It takes two parametes: (minimum) \c altitude 
above which reflectances are considered and   \c altitudeDev (altitude deviation), a fuzzy width parameter of the threshold. 

\~exec
  PROD=pMaxEcho,1000:9000 QUANTITY=DBZH ./make-image-product.sh #exec
\~
\include pMaxEcho.exm


The quality is low near and far from the radar, as precipitation may reside over and under radar beams,
respectively. 

\~remark
Further, quality is low in the highest-elevation bins with detected values; empty (undetected)
measurements "confirm" the maxima.  
\~

\image html  pMaxEcho-DBZH-panel.png "The maximum echo product and its quality field." 
\image latex pMaxEcho-DBZH-panel.png "The maximum echo product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth

 
\subsection echoTop  Echo top altitude

Height of precipitation can be computed with \c --pEchoTop command. It takes threshold reflectivity (dBZ) as its first argument.
\~exec
  PROD=pEchoTop,20 QUANTITY=HGHT INPUT=volume-conv.h5 ./make-image-product.sh #exec
\~
\include pEchoTop.exm

The other parameters are the coordinates of a hight reference point having a very low dBZ value. The echo top altitudes 
are linearly interpolated towards this point. 

The user may wish to choose a target resolution, for example:   
 \code
  rack volume.h5 --encoding C,0.05 --pEchoTop 20  -o echoTop_8bit.h5
  rack volume.h5 --encoding S,1.0  --pEchoTop 20  -o echoTop_16bit.h5
 \endcode
 

\image html  pEchoTop-HGHT-panel.png "Echo top product and its quality field." 
\image latex pEchoTop-HGHT-panel.png "Echo top product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth

\~remark
Echo top is an indirect measurement and its reliability varies strongly with the number and height of radar beams.
It can be measured rather reliably where a beam intersects the threshold reflectance.
In the image below, these locations are illustrated as circles.  
\image html  echoTop-principle.png "Estimation of echo top by means of reflectivity gradients." 
\image latex echoTop-principle.png "Estimation of echo top by means of reflectivity gradients." width=0.5\textwidth
In other cases, the echo top altitudes have to be interpolated using reflectivity measured along the beams.
In computation, \b Rack recognizes the following cases, illustrated in the above image:
