(Under constr.)




\subsection rainRate  Rainfall rate (mm/h)  (under construction)

Currently, \b rack provides two operators for estimating instantaneous rainfall rate: an operator using single and another using 
double polarization. The rate is estimated aloft, ie. on an elevation scan (by default the lowest one). 
That is, there is currently no actual surface rainfall rate estimation. The computation uses the following formulae: 
 
- \f$R(z) = \frac{1}{a}z^\frac{1}{b}\f$
- \f$R(z_{h},z_{dr})  = 0.0122z_{h}^{0.820}z_{dr}^{-2.28}\f$
- \f$R(K_{dp}) = 21.0K_{dp}^{0.720}\f$
- \f$R(K_{dp},z_{dr}) = 29.7K_{dp}^{0.890}z_{dr}^{-0.927}\f$

\~exec
  make precip{ZZDR,KDP,KDPZDR,Zsnow,Zrain}.hlp
  # ack --help formulae | fgrep Precip -i -A 1  > precip.inc 
\~
The parameters of these formulae can be changed with the respective commands: 
\include precipZrain.hlp
\include precipZsnow.hlp
\include precipZZDR.hlp
\include precipKDP.hlp
\include precipKDPZDR.hlp

These commands can be seen collectively also with \c --help \c formulae .

The simpler command \c  --pRainRate uses \c --precipZrain and \c --precipZsnow .
It assumes that a global freezing level is available in data as ODIM variable \c how:freeze [km].
To override that, the user may apply \c --freezingLevel to set the height and thickness of the freezing level.    

\~exec
  INPUT=volume-wide-conv.h5 PROD=pRainRate QUANTITY=RATE ./make-image-product.sh #exec
\~

\include pRainRate.exm


\image html  pRainRate-RATE-panel.png "Rain rate [mm/h] product and its quality field." 
\image latex pRainRate-RATE-panel.png "Rain rate [mm/h] product and its quality field." width=0.5\textwidth

\subsection RainRateDP Dual polarimetric rainfall rate (mm/h)

Calculates the rain rate using four different functions that utilize dbz, zdr and kdp data. The optimal
rain rate function is chosen for each radar data pixel using the given data threshold values. These thresholds are
adjustable and their values can be given from the command line, for example:

\code
 rack volume.h5 --pRainRateDP '0.85:50.0:20.0:0.2:0.1' -o <rainRateDP.h5>
\endcode
where the values are:

- 0.85 - rhohv meteorological target filter
- 50.0 - dbz hail/ice
- 20.0 - dbz heavy rain
- 0.2 - kdp heavy rain
- 0.1 - zdr threshold 

The functions are:\n
(1) \f$R={\frac{z}{a}}^\frac{1}{b}\f$\n
(2) \f$R=0.0122z_{h}^{0.820}z_{dr}^{-2.28}\f$\n
(3) \f$R=21.0K_{dp}^{0.720}\f$\n
(4) \f$R=29.7K_{dp}^{0.890}z_{dr}^{-0.927}\f$\n

The graph describes the rain rate calculation algorithm that mixes all the four methods. Dual pol. equations shouldn't be applied
if the measurement is done closer than 10 km from the radar. In addition, the equations should only be used for liquid water. These
factors have been taken into consideration in the implementation and Eq.1 is used when ever the other equations can't be applied.  
\dot
  digraph rainRateDP {

	size="9,5";
 	rankdir=UD;
 	
	node [shape=record, fontsize=10];
    edge [color=black, fontsize=10];
	
	metfilter [label="rhohv greater than 0.85"];
	nonmet [label="R=0"];
	
	hailice [label="dbz greater than 50"];
	hailicezdr [label="zdr greater than 0.1"];
	hailice3 [label="Eq. 3"];
	hailice4 [label="Eq. 4"];
	heavyrain [label="dbz greater than 20\nkdp greater than 0.2"];
	heavyrainzdr [label="zdr 0.1"];
	heavyrain2 [label="Eq. 2"];
	heavyrain1 [label="Eq. 1"];
	
	metfilter -> nonmet [label="no"];
	metfilter -> hailice [label="yes"];
	hailice -> heavyrain [label="no"];
	hailice -> hailicezdr [label="yes"];
	hailicezdr -> hailice3 [label="no"];
	hailicezdr -> hailice4 [label="yes"];
	heavyrain -> heavyrainzdr [label="no"];
	heavyrain -> hailicezdr [label="yes"];
	heavyrainzdr -> heavyrain1 [label="no"];
	heavyrainzdr -> heavyrain2 [label="yes"];
}
\enddot



\section otherproducts Other single-radar products

\subsection verticalProfile  Vertical profile
 
Vertical distribution of reflectivity can be computed with \c --verticalProfile . It takes several arguments:

\~exec
PROD=pVerticalProfile ./make-image-product.sh #exec
\~
\include verticalProfile-params.inc

The default selector for this operator defines \c quantity=^DBZH$ but more quantities can included with \c --select .
The resulting product consists of one-dimensional arrays for height (\c HGHT ) and each input quantity stored in data groups, \c /dataset1/data<N> .
In addition to the native output format (HDF5), the resulting product can exported as an image (png) or text (mat format). The latter works only
if \c azSlots=1 , for example: 
\code
rack volume-conv-VIM.h5 --pVerticalProfile 40:200,0:11000,100,0:360,1 -o profile.mat
\endcode

\~exec
  ./make-profile.sh #exec 
\~

The text file consists of a header line and the quantities in column layout. Height (HGHT) will be always the first quantity:

\include profile-cut.mat

The text format suits well to further illustrations with appropriate software. The curve images below have been created with \b gnuplot . 

\image html  vpr-screen.png "A graphical interface using Rack for VPR computation." 
\image latex vpr-screen.png "A graphical interface using Rack for VPR computation." width=0.5\textwidth


Both the applied input quantities and the output quantities can be set with \c --select command. 
   
\~exec
  convert -frame 2 +append rhi-widespread-low.png rhi-conv.png -resize 75\% rhi-screen.png
  echo "TODO Wed, 14 Aug 2013 12:00:00 GMT   FIVAN"
\~


\subsection pseudoRhi Pseudo RHI 

While a true Range-height indicator (RHI) is obtained by tilting 
the radar antenna vertically, one may construct \e Pseudo RHI's
by computing an intersection in a standard measurement volume consisting of 
azimuthal sweeps. 

\include pPseudoRhi.hlp

Such a product is obtained with
\~cliconf
My_comment="foo"
\~
\code{.sh}
rack volume.h5 --pPseudoRhi 168,0:120,0:11000,800:400,0.25 -o pseudo-rhi.h5
\endcode

\b Experimental. Using Rack Python API, the respective product can be created with:
\~pyconf
{
	"prog": "python3",
	"head": [
		"my head"
		],
	"tail": [
		"ops.."
	]
}
\~
\code{.py}
fmt = rack.prog.RackFormatter(params_format="'{params}'")
rackProg = rack.prog.CommandSequence(programName='rack', quote="'")
Rack = rack.core.Rack(rackProg)
Rack.inputFile('volume.h5')
Rack.pPseudoRhi(168, range=[-50000,250000], height=[0,15000])
Rack.outputFile('pseudo-rhi.h5')
cmds = rackProg.to_list(fmt)
self.assertEqual(cmds, ['rack',
  "'volume.h5'",
  "--pPseudoRhi '168,-50000:250000,0:15000'",
  "--outputFile 'pseudo-rhi.h5'"])
\endcode


\~pyconf
prog: "python3",
head= "my head",test
"tail"= "ops.."
\~
\code{.py}
fmt2 = rack.prog.RackFormatter(params_format="'{params}'")
rackProg2 = rack.prog.CommandSequence(programName='rack', quote="'")
\endcode


The 2D data may be coloured with \c --palette command and saved as an image file. The gridded images below have been created from such images 
with \b gnuplot . 

\image html  rhi-screen.png "A graphical interface using Rack for Pseudo-RHI computation." 
\image latex rhi-screen.png "A graphical interface using Rack for Pseudo-RHI computation." width=0.5\textwidth


\section nonmetproducts Other useful products


\subsection beamAlt  Beam altitude 

For special applications, the height of the beam can be computed with \c --beamAltitude command. It takes the altitude reference point as argument (0=radar site, 
1=sea level), Target properties can be set with \c --encoding command:
image \c type (typically 'C' or 'd') as the first argument and \c gain (kilometres) as second. 
The resulting polar product is simply a function of ground distance, hence an array of \c nbins x 1 elements,
but can be projected to a Cartesian product like any other polar product.

\~exec
  PROD=pBeamAltitude QUANTITY=HGHT ./make-image-product.sh #exec 
\~
\include pBeamAltitude.exm

\include beamAltitude-params.inc

\~remark
  xack volume.h5 --select elangle=1 --pBeamAltitude '0' -c --palette palette-HGHT.txt  --paletteRefine 32  -o pBeamAltitude2.png
  xonvert +append pBeamAltitude-HGHT-panel.png pBeamAltitude2.png pBeamAltitude-HGHT-panel.png
\~


\image html  pBeamAltitude-HGHT-panel.png "Beam altitude product." 
\image latex pBeamAltitude-HGHT-panel.png "Beam altitude product." width=0.5\textwidth


